This paper is about Clinical Named Entity Recognition (CNER) using deep learning methods, which is a subfield of natural language processing (NLP) and falls under the Computer Science category. Specifically, the paper proposes a Residual Dilated Convolutional Neural Network with Conditional Random Field (RD-CNN-CRF) for CNER tasks. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CL (Computation and Language), which covers NLP and speech processing. The paper also mentions that the proposed method achieves faster training time compared to RNN-based methods, which suggests that it may also belong to the sub-categories of cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). Additionally, the use of dense vector representations and conditional random fields may suggest that the paper could also belong to the sub-categories of cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) and cs.IR (Information Retrieval), respectively.
